Clearly not. The creature was content to whistle and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Luckily, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she almost lost her grip on its too slick scales.
"How do you kill them?", Nyssi cried.
"SEE HOW THEY REACT!"
"This is not going to be easy!"
Thassalin blew, then made a loop to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed him, somewhat frantic when a bolt of fire struck him from behind. The creature hadn't noticed it was no longer alone. Its frenzy grew as Thassalin slowed down, then struck it violently on the head with his tail, making it deviate from its trajectory.
Grunting and whistling, the creature took altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the sky's light and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
Lacking any visibility, Thassalin tried to retreat, but grazed the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if she knew exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight for him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!", exclaimed Tenuk as he extricated himself from the cloud and began to fly in circles to try and spot Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What are we doing, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Downstairs, Nyssi managed to stand up as well as she could. She was sure she must have broken something, but her strange unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. The same could not be said of Thassalin, who was lying on a hummock, leaning against the only tree that hadn't bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try to reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed up in impious shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming.
A horrible club-like tail came crashing down beside Nyssi, knocking her over. She noted, however, that the tail was thrashing about, without targeting her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and clawing at the shadows it had conjured up. Something was teleporting through the darkness, hitting the monster and disorienting it.
A sudden gunshot echoed, and the monster fell silent and motionless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding his rifle and panting for breath.
"It's... the most bizarre leap of shadow I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped. His eyes gleamed with a black light, and a dark energy ran through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow color.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel was gifted with strange powers of darkness. He rarely used them, as most people considered them to be impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed just as surprised as well.
"Are you okay?", Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, as Tenuk made his way to land beside him, regaining his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could get a better look at it. Its skin was black like coal and sticky, but the saliva continued to adhere to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something let out a howl and leaped from a nearby bush. However, the beast was not given the chance to reach them, as a familiar vehicle slammed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Not taking any risks, the latter quickly grabbed her rifle and shot it right between the eyes, killing the creature instantly.
"Oh no...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily shutting off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "Uh, I didn't mean to do that. Are you okay?"
"You practically missed the whole action", Tenuk regretted. "Where were you?"
"You all dropped me. I came here as fast as I could", sighed Retvik. "Can we know what those wretched things are?"
Retvik's interrogation was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had just got up. He was cut and scratched all over and seemed a bit disoriented but didn't look too badly hurt.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPT! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"Do you mean... the horrible god monster we've... helped kill?", Tenuk stammered.
"YES, IT'S ALL GOOD. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO HIT THEM ON THE HEAD. I'M MISSING A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE, THAT'S NOT FAIR, RIGHT? " Thassalin walked over to Kayel and tapped him on the head. " THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS ABLE TO KILL UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I suppose", Kayel said with a shrug. "So, we're done here?"
Nissy shrugged her shoulders then grabbed her camera to photograph the now well-dead beasts. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the god of death, and began to cut off one of the animal's horns, before attacking the other. But just as she finished, the creatures ignited and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns Nissy had cut off.
"Well, it's both convenient and not at all convenient," she sighed. "At least, I have the photos..."
